Exam structure:

Part I [30%] - General Linear Algebra
I will select 3 of the following 6 exercise types, each worth 10%.
1. Relate information about the kernel and image of a matrix and the number of solutions to an equation, possibly using the rank-nullity theorem.
2. Given a linear subspace described by a spanning set, describe it via a basis and determine its dimension.
3. Invert a 3x3 matrix. Use the results to solve an equation.
4. Determine whether a vector is in the span of others. Determine whether a set of vectors is linearly dependent or independent.
5. Sketch subspaces of R2 described in the following manner: By Cartesian equations, by a spanning set, as the image of a matrix, as the kernel of a matrix.
6. Compare subspaces of Rn. For example: Determine whether the kernel of a matrix is the same as the kernel of another.

Part II [20%] - Geometry
1. [5%] Interpret the determinant as one of: Measure of a shape, measure change factor of a linear transformation, test of invertibility, etc.
2. [5%] Formally manipulate the determinant, using rules such as det(AB)=detA detB, etc.
3. [5%] Interpret the dot product and use it to calculate geometrical quantities.
4. [5%] Formally manipulate the dot product, using it to draw conclusions about statements regarding orthogonality.

Part III [50%] - Diagonalization
1. [20%] Diagonalize a 3x3 matrix with a repeated eigenvalue.
2. [20%] Interpret the results of diagonalization in the context of a discrete dynamical system, modeling some real-world phenomenon.
3. [10%] Miscellaneous question(s) about eigenvalues, eigenvectors, and diagonalization.


Here is where you may find the relevant section of the textbook for each of these. The textbook problems will serve as good practice, even if none of them match up exactly with the above descriptions.

I.1: Ch3.1.
I.2: Ch3.3.
I.3: Ch2.4
I.4: Ch3.3.
I.5: Ch3.1, Ch3.2.
I.6: Ch3.1, Ch3.2, Ch3.3.

II: Ch5, Ch6.

III: Ch7.1 up to Ch7.4.